While signing a message using PGP/MIME is straight-forward, Geary should use hybrid
encryption for encrypting a message - i.e. generate a transient, syymetric session key, use
that to encrypt the message, then for each recipient, encrypts the session key with the
recipient's public key and adds that to the message. This means the message body must
only be encrypted and included once, not once for each recipient. This is the same
approach taken by Enigmail.

If a sender address is selected with a valid key, then Geary should always
sign the message using PGP/MIME. A message should als be encrypted
when all recipients have valid keys, and no BCC recipients are specified
(since the hybrid encryption approach would leak the BCC recipients).
Ideally, Geary should indicate the status of keys for each individual
recipient. However since the To/CC/BCC fields are currently text entries,
some work may be required there to enable this, e.g. by replacing them
with labels, per: https://bugzilla.gnome.org/show_bug.cgi?id=713348
An alternative for the moment an icon can be added to the To/CC/BCC
text entries indicating the overall status for all recipients.
When all recipients have valid keys and no BCC recipients are specified,
and hence the message will be sent encrypted:
When some recipients have valid keys and/or BCC recipients are specified,
and hence the message will be sent signed only:
When a sender account without encryption is selected, no icon should be
shown.
Clicking on the icon could show a GtkPopover with summary of recipients
and their individual key status (trust, validity, etc). A tool tip for the icon
should offer a brief explaination, e.g. “Message will be sent encrypted” or
“Message be sent signed (1 recipient is missing a trusted key to encrypt)”
When recipient labels implemented, the label can indicate invalid keys and
clicking on that would show the details status for that recipient.
TBD: Decide what these popovers will look like.
Alice <alice@example.net>, Bob <bob@example.net>
